The old King, nevertheles, executed this with a great deal of Reluctancy; but he believ'd he had made a very great Conquet over himelf, when he had once reolv'd, and had perform'd what he reolv'd. He believ'd now, that his Love had been unjut; and that he cou'd not expect the Gods, or Captain of the Clouds (as • hey call the unknown Power)
wou'd uffer a better Conequence from o ill a Caue. He now begins to hold Oroonoko excus'd; and to ay, he had Reaon for what he did: And now every Body cou'd aure the King how paionately Imoinda was belov'd by the Prince; even thoe confes'd it now, who aid the contrary before his Flame was abated. So that the King being old, and not able to defend himelf in War, and having no Sons of all his Race remaining alive, but only this, to maintain him on his Throne; and looking on this as a Man dioblig'd, firt by the Rape of his Mitres, or rather Wife, and now by depriving of him wholly of her, he fear'd, might make him deperate, and do ome cruel thing, either to himelf or his old Grand-father the Offender; he began to repent him extremely of the Contempt he had, in his Rage, put on Imoinda. Beides, he conider'd, he ought in Honour to have kill'd her, for this Offence, if it had been one: He ought to have had o much Value and Conideration for a Maid of her Quality, as to have nobly put her to Death; and not to have old her like a common Slave, the greatet Revenge, and the mot digraceful of any; and to which they a thouand times preferr Death, and implore it; as Imoinda did, but cou'd not obtain that Honour. Seeing therefore it was certain, that Oroonoko wou'd highly reent this Affront, he thought good to make ome Excue for his Rahnes to him; and to that end, he ent a Meenger to the Camp, with Orders to treat with him about the Matter, to gain his Pardon, and to endeavour to mitigate his Grief;
but that by no means he hou'd tell him he was old, but ecretly put to death; for he knew he hou'd never obtain his Pardon for the other.

In the mean time, Ardelia, who, that fatal Night, but too rightly gues'd that the Death of one or both her Lovers was the caue that they did not return to their Promie, the next Day fell into a high Fever, in which her Father found her, oon after he had clear'd himelf of thoe who came to earch for her Lover. The aurance which her Father gave her of Henrique's Life eem'd a little to revive her; but the everity of Antonio's Fate was no way obliging to her, ince he cou'd not but retain the memory of his Love and Contancy; which added to her Afflictions, and heightned her Ditemper, inomuch that Richardo was contrain'd to leave her under the care of the good Lady Abbes, and to the diligent Attendance of Eleanora, not daring to hazard her Life in a removal to his own Houe. All their Care and Diligence was however ineffectual; for he languih'd even to the leat hope of Recovery, till immediately after the firt Viit of Don Henrique, which was the firt he made in a Month's time, and that by Night, incognito, with her Father, her Ditemper viibly retreated each day: yet when at lat he enjoy'd a perfect Health of Body, her Mind grew ick, and he plung'd into a deep Melancholy; which made
her entertain a poitive Reolution of taking the Veil at the end of her Novitiate: which accordingly he did, notwithtanding all the Entreaties, Prayers and Tears both of her Father and Lover. But he oon repented her Vow, and often wih'd that he might by any means ee and peak to Don Henrique, by whoe help he promis'd to her elf a Deliverance out of her voluntary Imprionment: Nor were his Wihes wanting to the ame effect, though he was forc'd to flie into Italy, to avoid the Proecution of Antonio's Friends. Thither he puru'd him; nor cou'd he any way hun her, unles he cou'd have left his Heart at a ditance from his Body: Which made him take a fatal Reolution of returning to Sevil in Diguie; where he wander'd about the Convent every Night like a Ghot, (for indeed his Soul was within, while his Inanimate Trunk was without,) till at lat he found means to convey a Letter to her, which both urpriz'd and delighted her. The Meenger that brought it her, was one of her Mother-in-Laws Maids, whom he had known before, and met accidentally one night as he was going his Rounds, and he coming out from Ardelia; with her he prevail'd, and with Gold oblig'd her to Secrecy and Aitance: which prov'd o uccesful, that he undertood from Ardelia her trong deire of Liberty, and the continuance of her Paion for him, together with the Means and Time mot convenient and likely to ucceed for her Enlargement. The Time was the Fourteenth Night following, at Twelve a clock, which jut compleated a Month ince his return thither;
at which time they Both promis'd themelves the greatet Happines on Earth. But you may oberve the jutice of Heaven, in their Diappointment.

ABout the beginning of lat June (as near as I can remember) Bellamora came to Town from Hamphire; and was oblig'd to lodge the firt Night at the ame Inn where the Stage-Coach et up. The next Day he took Coach for Covent-Garden, where he thought to find Madam Brightly, a Relation of her's; with whom he deign'd to continue for about half a Year undicover'd, if poible, by her Friends in the Country: And order'd therefore her Trunk, with her Cloaths, and mot of her Money and Jewels, to be brought after her to Madam Brightly's, by a trange Porter whom he poke to in the Street as he was taking Coach; being utterly unacquainted with the neat Practices of this fine City. When he came to Bridges-treet, where indeed her Couin had lodged near three or four Years ince;
he was trangely urpriz'd that he cou'd not learn any thing of her; no, nor o much as meet with any one that had ever heard of her Couin's Name. Till, at lat, decribing Madam Brightly to one of the Houe-keepers in that place, he told her, that there was uch a kind of Lady, whom he had ometimes een there about a Year and a half ago; but that he believ'd, he was married and remov'd towards So-ho. In this Perplexity he quite forgot her Trunk and Money, &c. and wander'd in her Hackney-Coach all over St. Ann's Parih; inquiring for Madam Brightly, till decribing her Peron, but in vain; for no Soul cou'd give her any Tale or Tidings of uch a Lady. After he had thus fruitlely rambled, till he, the Coachman, and the very Hores were e'en tir'd, by good Fortune for her, he happen'd on a private-Houe, were lived a good, dicreet, ancient Gentlewoman, who was fallen a little to decay, and was forc'd to let Lodgings for the bet part of her Livelihood: From whom he undertood, that there was uch a kind of a Lady who had lain there omewhat more than a Twelve-month, being near three Months after he was married: But that he was now gone abroad with the Gentleman her Husband; either to the Play, or to take the freh Air; and he believ'd, wou'd not return till Night. This Dicoure of the good Gentlewoman's o elevated Bellamora's drooping Spirits, that after he had begg'd the Liberty of taying there till they came home, he dicharg'd the Coachman in all hate, till forgetting
her Trunk, and the more valuable Furniture of it.
